1
00:00:11,428 --> 00:00:14,264
Today, people, we are
privileged to have with us

2
00:00:14,306 --> 00:00:17,392
a former Labor Cabinet Minister
and leader of the House of Lords,

3
00:00:17,434 --> 00:00:20,812
a Knight of the Garter
and Seventh Earl of Longford

4
00:00:20,854 --> 00:00:23,315
who's come to talk to us
about a book he's just written

5
00:00:23,357 --> 00:00:25,567
entitled, "Saints."

6
00:00:25,609 --> 00:00:28,111
Frank Packenham, Lord Longford,
welcome to the show.

7
00:00:28,153 --> 00:00:29,821
Thank you very much.

8
00:00:29,863 --> 00:00:32,908
So many questions to ask you,
such a long and distinguished career,

9
00:00:32,950 --> 00:00:35,786
but I'm gonna start with the book.
What prompted you to write it?

10
00:00:35,786 --> 00:00:38,413
As a lifelong Christian
and scholar,

11
00:00:38,455 --> 00:00:42,584
I've always been interested
in ideas of sanctity.

12
00:00:42,626 --> 00:00:45,462
But more than that,
I think it was probably

13
00:00:45,462 --> 00:00:49,174
the entirely selfish desire to spend
a little time with my heroes.

14
00:00:49,216 --> 00:00:51,927
- Your heroes?
- Yes, that's what the saints are...

15
00:00:51,969 --> 00:00:55,264
my heroes, friends,
intercessors.

16
00:00:55,305 --> 00:00:59,393
Interesting. Right,
the time has just gone 2:15.

17
00:00:59,434 --> 00:01:02,145
The subject is "Saints."
We're gonna take some calls.

18
00:01:02,187 --> 00:01:05,274
David, you're through
to Lord Longford.

19
00:01:05,315 --> 00:01:07,568
What's your question
about the saints?

20
00:01:07,609 --> 00:01:10,070
Actually, my question
isn't about the saints.

21
00:01:10,112 --> 00:01:11,780
I want to know how
your esteemed guest

22
00:01:11,822 --> 00:01:13,824
can look himself
in the mirror each morning.

23
00:01:13,824 --> 00:01:16,994
I'm assuming this is
a question about Myra Hindley.

24
00:01:17,035 --> 00:01:18,579
Yes, it is.
How could you rub salt

25
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:20,455
in the wounds of
the families like that?

26
00:01:20,497 --> 00:01:22,958
A man in your position
fraternizing and campaigning

27
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:24,334
on behalf of that monster?

28
00:01:24,376 --> 00:01:26,503
I certainly take exception
to that description,

29
00:01:26,545 --> 00:01:29,006
but I made it quite clear
before coming on the program

30
00:01:29,006 --> 00:01:31,508
that I wouldn't be talking
about Myra Hindley today.

31
00:01:31,508 --> 00:01:34,970
Of course. Next caller is Judy
who's in Sheppey.

32
00:01:35,012 --> 00:01:36,889
You're through
to Lord Longford.

33
00:01:36,930 --> 00:01:38,640
My call is also
about Ms. Hindley.

34
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:41,143
In view of everything
we now know about it,

35
00:01:41,185 --> 00:01:43,687
don't you regret having
supported her all that time?

36
00:01:43,687 --> 00:01:46,857
Once again, madam, I'm afraid I must
decline to answer questions about her.

37
00:01:46,899 --> 00:01:49,985
It's a simple answer,
Lord Longford... yes or no.

38
00:01:50,027 --> 00:01:52,654
Do you regret it?

39
00:02:06,627 --> 00:02:08,587
The Pennine Moorlands,

40
00:02:08,629 --> 00:02:11,673
scene of one of the most intensive
murder hunts of the century.

41
00:02:11,715 --> 00:02:13,884
Police and hundreds
of volunteers

42
00:02:13,926 --> 00:02:17,513
continue their gruesome search
for the bodies of murder victims,

43
00:02:17,554 --> 00:02:20,098
working on a scant tip-off
that the bleak moors

44
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:23,435
hide the evidence
of a mass murderer.

45
00:02:27,231 --> 00:02:29,858
And late on Saturday afternoon
they found the body

46
00:02:29,900 --> 00:02:33,070
of 10-year-old
Lesley Downey,

47
00:02:33,111 --> 00:02:35,280
face down
in a shallow grave.

48
00:02:37,324 --> 00:02:40,369
Five days later,
another body was discovered.

49
00:02:40,410 --> 00:02:43,705
...been identified as
that of John Kilbride,

50
00:02:43,747 --> 00:02:45,707
the 12-year-old boy
who disappeared

51
00:02:45,749 --> 00:02:48,085
from his Manchester home
nearly two years ago.

52
00:02:50,754 --> 00:02:52,881
I'm standing outside
number 16

53
00:02:52,923 --> 00:02:54,758
Wardle Brook Avenue,
Hattersley,

54
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:57,427
where earlier today police
arrested a man and a woman

55
00:02:57,469 --> 00:03:00,305
after finding the body
of a 17-year-old boy,

56
00:03:00,347 --> 00:03:02,558
Edward Evans.

57
00:03:02,599 --> 00:03:05,894
Police have now released
the names of the suspects.

58
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:09,231
They are Ian Brady,
a 28-year-old clerk,

59
00:03:09,273 --> 00:03:12,693
and Myra Hindley,
his 23-year-old girlfriend.

60
00:03:16,238 --> 00:03:19,032
Hindley, who said that
she had a sore throat,

61
00:03:19,074 --> 00:03:21,535
gave her evidence
in a low, husky voice.

62
00:03:21,577 --> 00:03:23,662
She said that she
had loved Brady

63
00:03:23,704 --> 00:03:25,539
and still loved him.

64
00:03:25,581 --> 00:03:28,750
When she was cross-examined about her
part in the nude photographing session

65
00:03:28,792 --> 00:03:30,919
with the child
Lesley Ann Downey,

66
00:03:30,961 --> 00:03:33,797
she said, "I offer
no defense for that.

67
00:03:33,839 --> 00:03:35,757
It was indefensible
and cruel."

68
00:03:35,799 --> 00:03:39,178
She said she didn't know that Brady
was tape-recording the session

69
00:03:39,219 --> 00:03:42,264
and that she was ashamed
when she heard the tape played later.

70
00:03:42,306 --> 00:03:44,933
Extra police were
called in to keep the peace.

71
00:03:44,975 --> 00:03:48,270
The parents of other missing Manchester
children were outside the court.

72
00:03:48,312 --> 00:03:51,106
- Hanging's too good for them.
- This was too quick.

73
00:03:51,148 --> 00:03:53,609
He wants to torture them.

74
00:03:53,650 --> 00:03:55,777
A tooth for a tooth
and a life for a life.

75
00:03:55,819 --> 00:03:58,363
...head sank as she heard
the foreman of the jury

76
00:03:58,405 --> 00:04:01,116
speak the word "guilty"
the first time.

77
00:04:01,158 --> 00:04:04,995
"These were three calculated,
cruel and cold-blooded murders,"

78
00:04:05,037 --> 00:04:07,456
was what Mr. Justice
Fenton Atkinson said.

79
00:04:07,497 --> 00:04:10,667
Sentencing them both
to life imprisonment,

80
00:04:10,709 --> 00:04:14,379
the judge said quietly,
"Put them down."

81
00:04:32,189 --> 00:04:34,316
From time to time,

82
00:04:34,358 --> 00:04:36,485
people are kind enough
to ask me what I consider

83
00:04:36,527 --> 00:04:38,403
to be my greatest
achievement in life,

84
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:40,239
and I always answer
the same way.

85
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:43,825
I say, "It is that
I visit prisoners."

86
00:04:43,867 --> 00:04:45,994
Congratulations, Roy.

87
00:04:46,036 --> 00:04:47,829
And if I were to die tonight,

88
00:04:47,871 --> 00:04:50,999
it is the very first thing
I would say to St. Peter

89
00:04:51,041 --> 00:04:52,334
if he were remotely
interested.

90
00:04:52,376 --> 00:04:54,503
Morning, Barry.

91
00:04:54,545 --> 00:04:58,173
But some of my greatest
and most-valued friendships

92
00:04:58,215 --> 00:05:01,009
have begun
with prison visits.

93
00:05:01,051 --> 00:05:05,681
And much of what I've learned,
I owe to prison visits.

94
00:05:05,722 --> 00:05:09,601
Dennis here, for example,
has taught me the workings

95
00:05:09,643 --> 00:05:12,020
of the diesel engine.

96
00:05:12,062 --> 00:05:14,022
Priceless information...

97
00:05:14,064 --> 00:05:17,526
even though I do not drive.

98
00:05:17,568 --> 00:05:20,737
and Michael here
has taught me Gaelic.

99
00:05:20,779 --> 00:05:24,533
And together we have studied
some of Ireland's finest poetry.

100
00:05:24,575 --> 00:05:27,119
And I thank you
for that, Michael.

101
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:29,246
And Roy here,

102
00:05:29,288 --> 00:05:31,874
whose release we are
celebrating today,

103
00:05:31,915 --> 00:05:36,044
has taught me that it is never too
late to take up something new

104
00:05:36,086 --> 00:05:38,213
and to still master it.

105
00:05:38,255 --> 00:05:41,884
Having never so much as picked
up a brush before the age of 30,

106
00:05:41,925 --> 00:05:45,762
he is this year to be shown
at the Royal Academy.

107
00:05:51,059 --> 00:05:53,645
In fact, I have
an example of that here,

108
00:05:53,687 --> 00:05:55,439
which has just been
presented to me.

109
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:57,733
It's a very fine
piece of work.

110
00:05:57,774 --> 00:06:01,945
I think you could've chosen
a rather more attractive subject, Roy,

111
00:06:01,987 --> 00:06:03,655
and you flatter me
a great deal.

112
00:06:03,697 --> 00:06:05,824
Thank you very much.

113
00:06:12,664 --> 00:06:14,291
Might I have a word?

114
00:06:14,333 --> 00:06:15,918
- Yes, of course.
- In private.

115
00:06:15,959 --> 00:06:17,503
Yes, of course.

116
00:06:19,463 --> 00:06:22,132
Excuse me.

117
00:06:22,174 --> 00:06:26,261
I just had a phone call
from the governor of Holloway Prison.

118
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:29,264
So what did
Ann Tree want?

119
00:06:29,306 --> 00:06:32,518
Oh, the mighty Tree.

120
00:06:32,559 --> 00:06:36,605
There's a prisoner in Holloway
who specifically asked to see me.

121
00:06:36,647 --> 00:06:38,815
As long as it's not
Myra Hindley.

122
00:06:38,857 --> 00:06:41,318
As a matter of fact,
it is.

123
00:06:52,871 --> 00:06:54,957
You're not going to go?

124
00:06:54,998 --> 00:06:56,834
Of course.

125
00:06:56,875 --> 00:06:59,461
I can't sit on the board
of a prison-visiting charity

126
00:06:59,503 --> 00:07:01,463
and start drawing lines.

127
00:07:01,505 --> 00:07:03,465
Yes, you can.

128
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:05,509
Frank, that woman's inhuman.

129
00:07:05,551 --> 00:07:08,512
She's... she's a monster.

130
00:07:08,554 --> 00:07:11,306
She murdered innocent
young children.

131
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:12,975
We don't even
know how many.

132
00:07:13,016 --> 00:07:15,853
But as a prisoner, she's still
perfectly entitled to be visited.

133
00:07:15,853 --> 00:07:18,355
Yes, but not
necessarily by you.

134
00:07:20,274 --> 00:07:24,236
Look, you know I've always
supported your penal work,

135
00:07:24,278 --> 00:07:26,989
but there are some crimes,
some people that are...

136
00:07:27,030 --> 00:07:29,658
What?
Unforgivable.

137
00:07:29,700 --> 00:07:31,952
Oh, come along, you know
what I feel about that.

138
00:07:31,994 --> 00:07:34,538
No human being is
beyond forgiveness.

139
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:37,499
Condemn people from our armchairs
and what have we become?

140
00:07:56,727 --> 00:07:59,813
Frank, stay behind
a moment, will you?

141
00:07:59,855 --> 00:08:02,316
Yes, of course,
Prime Minister.

142
00:08:06,528 --> 00:08:09,865
I read in the paper
you threw a party for a murderer

143
00:08:09,907 --> 00:08:11,408
in the House
of Lords yesterday.

144
00:08:11,450 --> 00:08:13,035
A released murderer,
Prime Minister,

145
00:08:13,076 --> 00:08:15,454
who's paid his debt to society
and is now free.

146
00:08:15,495 --> 00:08:17,789
Still made
the headlines.

147
00:08:17,831 --> 00:08:19,833
Wrong sort
of headlines.

148
00:08:19,875 --> 00:08:23,879
I understand your charitable
and philanthropic work is important,

149
00:08:23,921 --> 00:08:26,757
but holding this government together
is important to me.

150
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:30,427
You've a habit of doing this,
haven't you?

151
00:08:30,469 --> 00:08:32,763
Attracting
unfortunate headlines.

152
00:08:32,804 --> 00:08:35,641
I remember you asking

153
00:08:35,682 --> 00:08:38,227
your country to forgive
the Germans after the war.

154
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:40,145
They were starving,
Prime Minister.

155
00:08:40,187 --> 00:08:42,439
But so were we.
It was 1947.

156
00:08:45,317 --> 00:08:48,779
There's an endearing
childlike quality about you, Frank.

157
00:08:50,697 --> 00:08:52,741
But no one wants
children in cabinet.

158
00:08:54,535 --> 00:08:58,247
I made you leader of the Lords
on the recommendation of Clem Attlee.

159
00:08:58,288 --> 00:09:02,835
And so far, you've done
little to justify his faith.

160
00:09:02,876 --> 00:09:06,588
But, you have a talent...

161
00:09:08,340 --> 00:09:09,925
Which I will utilize.

162
00:09:09,967 --> 00:09:12,094
And then he came up
with this report...

163
00:09:12,135 --> 00:09:14,096
well, not a report,
more of an investigation.

164
00:09:14,137 --> 00:09:16,682
He wants me to look
into young people nationwide,

165
00:09:16,723 --> 00:09:19,434
focusing on education,
homelessness, criminality.

166
00:09:19,476 --> 00:09:22,604
But you'd do that wonderfully.
I can't think of anyone better.

167
00:09:22,646 --> 00:09:26,275
Under normal circumstances, perhaps,
but this is clearly a poisoned chalice.

168
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:28,944
Half the inquiry would
come under the auspices of Education,

169
00:09:28,986 --> 00:09:30,362
and half under
the Home Office.

170
00:09:30,404 --> 00:09:32,281
Oh, I shouldn't have
come out tonight.

171
00:09:32,322 --> 00:09:34,283
- Don't be silly.
- Love to you.

172
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:36,827
Look, there's that lady
from "The Sunday Times"

173
00:09:36,869 --> 00:09:38,829
who wrote those lovely
things about you.

174
00:09:38,829 --> 00:09:40,455
Oh?

175
00:09:40,497 --> 00:09:42,541
Do you remember
how much you liked her?

176
00:09:42,583 --> 00:09:45,377
Oh, yes.

177
00:09:45,419 --> 00:09:48,422
Hello.
Very nice to see you.

178
00:09:50,007 --> 00:09:51,967
I'd like you to clear
an afternoon for me

179
00:09:52,009 --> 00:09:54,011
in the next couple
of weeks.

180
00:09:54,011 --> 00:09:55,762
- How's the 21st?
- You have a meeting at 4:00

181
00:09:55,804 --> 00:09:57,139
with the Home Secretary.

182
00:09:57,181 --> 00:09:59,057
- 28th?
- Better.

183
00:09:59,099 --> 00:10:00,976
I can move that one.

184
00:10:01,018 --> 00:10:03,145
Good,
let's go for the 28th.

185
00:10:11,195 --> 00:10:14,156
- What shall I put down?
- Hmm?

186
00:10:14,198 --> 00:10:16,325
Oh, just put "prison visit."

187
00:10:28,212 --> 00:10:30,672
Bernadette Collins?

188
00:10:30,714 --> 00:10:33,800
Susan Davis?

189
00:10:33,842 --> 00:10:36,512
Helen Kroger?

190
00:10:36,553 --> 00:10:40,516
Ethel G?

191
00:10:40,557 --> 00:10:42,267
Myra Hindley?

192
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:58,992
Susanna Smit?
Rita Williams?

193
00:11:27,104 --> 00:11:29,439
Ms. Hindley?

194
00:11:29,481 --> 00:11:32,401
I do beg your pardon,
madam.

195
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:51,253
I think it's me
you're looking for.

196
00:11:51,295 --> 00:11:53,130
Myra Hindley?

197
00:12:01,305 --> 00:12:03,307
Got rid of the peroxide
before the trial.

198
00:12:03,348 --> 00:12:05,559
It was blue at the trial
for most of it,

199
00:12:05,601 --> 00:12:07,352
and then red
for the sentencing.

200
00:12:07,394 --> 00:12:09,855
Apparently it
counted against me.

201
00:12:09,897 --> 00:12:11,940
It showed I had
no remorse.

202
00:12:11,982 --> 00:12:14,693
I wasn't aware
of a correlation

203
00:12:14,735 --> 00:12:17,654
between hair color
and contrition.

204
00:12:17,696 --> 00:12:19,948
Nor me.

205
00:12:19,990 --> 00:12:21,783
I'm very pleased
to meet you.

206
00:12:21,825 --> 00:12:26,663
Never met a Lord before.
What should I call you?

207
00:12:26,705 --> 00:12:28,874
M'lord?
Your grace?

208
00:12:28,916 --> 00:12:32,294
- You must call me Frank.
- All right. Frank.

209
00:12:32,336 --> 00:12:35,172
They put me in this
table in the corner

210
00:12:35,214 --> 00:12:38,717
'cause it helps protect me
from the lip readers.

211
00:12:38,759 --> 00:12:42,012
So, you specifically
asked to see me.

212
00:12:42,054 --> 00:12:43,514
What can I do for you?

213
00:12:43,514 --> 00:12:45,682
I want to see Ian Brady.

214
00:12:46,767 --> 00:12:48,352
I see.

215
00:12:48,393 --> 00:12:50,354
Although
we weren't married,

216
00:12:50,395 --> 00:12:52,689
we were together for six years,
which I believe

217
00:12:52,731 --> 00:12:54,775
makes us common-law
husband and wife,

218
00:12:54,816 --> 00:12:57,027
and therefore entitled
to see one another

219
00:12:57,069 --> 00:12:59,738
just like
married prisoners.

220
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:02,491
Well, if that's
what you desire,

221
00:13:02,533 --> 00:13:05,160
of course I will do
all I can to help you.

222
00:13:05,202 --> 00:13:07,913
But I have to say,
even though I'm not your solicitor,

223
00:13:07,955 --> 00:13:09,581
I don't think
it's a good idea.

224
00:13:09,623 --> 00:13:11,416
Why not?

225
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:14,169
Because whatever it is you wish
to achieve by seeing him,

226
00:13:14,211 --> 00:13:16,505
it will almost
certainly elude you.

227
00:13:16,547 --> 00:13:19,633
If it's private conversation
or intimate contact you're after,

228
00:13:19,675 --> 00:13:21,510
you won't get it.
You'll be surrounded

229
00:13:21,552 --> 00:13:23,595
by prison officers
and guards at all times.

230
00:13:23,637 --> 00:13:27,349
Then there's the question
of public reaction.

231
00:13:27,391 --> 00:13:30,352
Were the press to get hold
of it, they'd have a field day.

232
00:13:30,394 --> 00:13:33,146
It might have a profoundly
detrimental effect

233
00:13:33,188 --> 00:13:35,232
on any future
chances of parole.

234
00:13:37,651 --> 00:13:39,778
Parole?

235
00:13:39,820 --> 00:13:41,947
Lord Longford, have you
forgotten who I am?

236
00:13:41,989 --> 00:13:44,241
They'll never
give me parole.

237
00:13:44,283 --> 00:13:45,951
Why ever not?

238
00:13:45,993 --> 00:13:48,537
As I recall, the judge
made a distinction

239
00:13:48,579 --> 00:13:50,372
between your case
and Mr. Brady's.

240
00:13:50,414 --> 00:13:54,710
Although he sentenced him
for the rest of his natural life,

241
00:13:54,751 --> 00:13:58,046
he made it quite clear that
in your case, it could be reviewed.

242
00:13:58,088 --> 00:14:01,133
Now the average
life sentence

243
00:14:01,175 --> 00:14:03,844
is currently 21 years.

244
00:14:05,429 --> 00:14:08,849
Parole can be applied for
after a third of that time.

245
00:14:08,932 --> 00:14:12,811
So you can make your
first application...

246
00:14:12,853 --> 00:14:15,063
six years from now.

247
00:14:15,105 --> 00:14:17,441
Are you serious?

248
00:14:17,482 --> 00:14:19,401
Perfectly serious.

249
00:14:19,443 --> 00:14:21,695
God.

250
00:14:21,737 --> 00:14:23,488
So my advice would be

251
00:14:23,530 --> 00:14:26,450
that you put some distance
between yourself and Mr. Brady.

252
00:14:26,491 --> 00:14:30,871
I gave that man everything...

253
00:14:30,913 --> 00:14:35,292
my heart, my soul,

254
00:14:35,334 --> 00:14:37,002
my life.

255
00:14:37,044 --> 00:14:38,837
Indeed,
if I may say so,

256
00:14:38,879 --> 00:14:41,006
at some personal cost
to yourself.

257
00:14:42,216 --> 00:14:44,176
You're right.

258
00:14:44,218 --> 00:14:46,470
What a pretty smile
you have.

259
00:14:46,512 --> 00:14:47,930
What?

260
00:14:47,971 --> 00:14:50,349
I said
what a pretty smile.

261
00:14:50,390 --> 00:14:53,435
That's the first kind thing
anyone's said to me in months.

262
00:14:53,477 --> 00:14:54,978
It's true.

263
00:14:55,020 --> 00:14:57,856
As a matter of fact,
your entire appearance

264
00:14:57,898 --> 00:15:01,443
and demeanor is quite different
to what I expected.

265
00:15:01,485 --> 00:15:05,239
Of course, all I had to go on
was that police photograph.

266
00:15:07,199 --> 00:15:09,868
The Medusa.
That's what I call it.

267
00:15:09,910 --> 00:15:12,246
No one looks their best
at 4:00 in the morning

268
00:15:12,287 --> 00:15:14,665
having been questioned
for nine hours straight, do they?

269
00:15:14,706 --> 00:15:17,376
Five minutes!

270
00:15:17,417 --> 00:15:19,962
So, is there anything
I can send you

271
00:15:20,003 --> 00:15:22,130
that would make things
more comfortable?

272
00:15:22,172 --> 00:15:24,967
Books and music.

273
00:15:25,008 --> 00:15:26,677
Anything in particular?

274
00:15:26,718 --> 00:15:29,471
I like jazz
and the Goons.

275
00:15:29,513 --> 00:15:32,182
Ian and I used
to listen to them a lot.

276
00:15:32,224 --> 00:15:33,851
I'll see
what I can do.

277
00:15:33,892 --> 00:15:36,645
In the meantime, I suggest
you get a family member

278
00:15:36,687 --> 00:15:38,647
to put aside half a pound
a week or so.

279
00:15:38,689 --> 00:15:42,317
- What for?
- When you come out.

280
00:15:42,359 --> 00:15:44,361
You really think
I will one day?

281
00:15:44,403 --> 00:15:46,405
Yes, of course.

282
00:15:49,283 --> 00:15:51,493
When will you come again?

283
00:15:51,535 --> 00:15:54,496
When you ask me.
Prison visitors never visit prisoners

284
00:15:54,538 --> 00:15:56,206
unless they're invited.

285
00:15:56,248 --> 00:15:59,835
Well, you'll hear
from me soon then.

286
00:15:59,877 --> 00:16:02,087
Good.

287
00:16:04,047 --> 00:16:06,675
Delighted to have
met you, Ms. Hindley.

288
00:16:06,717 --> 00:16:08,510
You too, Frank.

289
00:16:08,552 --> 00:16:10,846
Bye-bye.

290
00:16:23,108 --> 00:16:26,236
Anyway, she wasn't at all
how I might've expected.

291
00:16:26,278 --> 00:16:29,740
I've found her charming,
intelligent, attractive even.

292
00:16:29,781 --> 00:16:31,283
Ahem.

293
00:16:31,325 --> 00:16:34,745
A woman that murdered
three children?

294
00:16:34,745 --> 00:16:38,290
A woman who came under the spell
of a man who murdered three children.

295
00:16:38,332 --> 00:16:41,043
- That's rubbish.
- I spoke to the prison governor.

296
00:16:41,084 --> 00:16:44,922
She's quite convinced that Myra Hindley
was corrupted by Ian Brady

297
00:16:44,963 --> 00:16:48,050
and to consider them
as equals is a great mistake.

298
00:16:48,091 --> 00:16:50,469
Dada, except that she
procured those children,

299
00:16:50,511 --> 00:16:52,638
knowing exactly what
would happen to them.

300
00:16:52,679 --> 00:16:55,557
Never would've got into the car
without a woman present.

301
00:16:55,599 --> 00:16:57,768
The judge made a clear
distinction at the trial

302
00:16:57,809 --> 00:17:00,270
that Ian Brady was the initiator
of these crimes

303
00:17:00,312 --> 00:17:01,897
and the actual killer.

304
00:17:01,939 --> 00:17:04,983
Myra Hindley was merely a dominated
and corrupted accomplice.

305
00:17:05,025 --> 00:17:07,069
The distinction's irrelevant...
murderer and accomplice

306
00:17:07,110 --> 00:17:08,904
are equally guilty
in the eyes of the law.

307
00:17:08,946 --> 00:17:12,241
Killers of this kind almost always
have a prior history of offending.

308
00:17:12,282 --> 00:17:14,451
Myra Hindley had nothing,
not even a blemish.

309
00:17:14,493 --> 00:17:17,412
- and wasn't there a tape?
- what tape?

310
00:17:17,454 --> 00:17:19,623
At the trial. I seem to remember
there was a tape

311
00:17:19,665 --> 00:17:22,709
where one heard the dreadful things
they did to the little girl,

312
00:17:22,751 --> 00:17:25,420
and that it was Myra Hindley's voice
one could hear.

313
00:17:25,462 --> 00:17:30,342
- Not Brady's.
- No. What about a swim?

314
00:17:30,384 --> 00:17:33,095
Yes, please, grandpa.

315
00:17:33,136 --> 00:17:36,348
Please, Mommy,
a swim, a swim!

316
00:17:38,058 --> 00:17:41,645
I think
it's clearing up.

317
00:17:45,065 --> 00:17:46,984
"Dear Frank,

318
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:50,612
thanks again for your visit,

319
00:17:50,654 --> 00:17:52,489
for the books you sent me.

320
00:17:52,531 --> 00:17:56,285
I finished the first volume
of your autobiography."

321
00:17:56,326 --> 00:17:58,245
- How old are you then?
- 17.

322
00:17:58,287 --> 00:17:59,663
"It's an interesting life
you have had."

323
00:17:59,705 --> 00:18:01,790
You look younger to me.

324
00:18:01,832 --> 00:18:05,460
"So many conversions...

325
00:18:05,502 --> 00:18:07,421
from English to Irish;

326
00:18:07,462 --> 00:18:10,257
from conservative
to socialist;

327
00:18:10,299 --> 00:18:12,634
from Protestant
to Catholic.

328
00:18:12,676 --> 00:18:15,220
I don't know
if you're aware,

329
00:18:15,262 --> 00:18:19,183
but as a teenager I converted
to the Catholic church too."

330
00:18:19,183 --> 00:18:21,852
"Dear Myra,

331
00:18:21,894 --> 00:18:25,647
I had no idea that you had
converted to Catholicism too.

332
00:18:25,689 --> 00:18:28,150
How fascinating.

333
00:18:28,192 --> 00:18:29,902
What a coincidence."

334
00:18:29,943 --> 00:18:32,654
- May I?
- Mmm-hmm.

335
00:18:32,696 --> 00:18:36,742
As a young man, I wasn't
much interested in God.

336
00:18:36,783 --> 00:18:38,577
Quite the opposite.

337
00:18:38,619 --> 00:18:41,079
This one day I was
just overwhelmed

338
00:18:41,121 --> 00:18:42,831
by the sheer pointlessness

339
00:18:42,873 --> 00:18:46,001
of an existence without
the prospect of an afterlife.

340
00:18:46,043 --> 00:18:50,339
That's when I realized
that without a religious dimension,

341
00:18:50,380 --> 00:18:52,466
there was little
meaning to life."

342
00:18:55,594 --> 00:18:58,847
How's your spiritual
life now?

343
00:18:58,889 --> 00:19:03,352
I don't go to church anymore
if that's what you're asking.

344
00:19:03,393 --> 00:19:07,231
That all stopped when
I started seeing Ian...

345
00:19:08,982 --> 00:19:11,527
Along with everything else
that was good in my life.

346
00:19:16,114 --> 00:19:18,367
It's too powerful...

347
00:19:18,408 --> 00:19:21,787
a magnetlike
personality.

348
00:19:21,828 --> 00:19:26,375
He demolished everything
I believed in.

349
00:19:26,416 --> 00:19:30,003
I was obsessed.

350
00:19:32,089 --> 00:19:34,675
Next time you have a moment,
try going back to church.

351
00:19:34,716 --> 00:19:37,302
You might be
pleasantly surprised.

352
00:19:37,344 --> 00:19:40,973
In my experience, it's the prisoners
with the strongest faith

353
00:19:41,014 --> 00:19:44,434
that cope best.

354
00:19:44,476 --> 00:19:48,564
Just imagine what Ian
would say to that.

355
00:19:48,605 --> 00:19:52,943
He thinks God is for nutters.

356
00:19:52,985 --> 00:19:55,863
Does he?
Well, I beg to differ.

357
00:19:57,698 --> 00:19:59,449
"Dear Frank,

358
00:19:59,491 --> 00:20:01,743
the Catholic priest that
visits us here is German...

359
00:20:01,785 --> 00:20:04,329
Father Kahle.

360
00:20:04,371 --> 00:20:06,290
He says Mass here
twice a week,

361
00:20:06,331 --> 00:20:08,584
and last week I told him
I might be looking

362
00:20:08,625 --> 00:20:10,627
to find a way back
to the church."

363
00:20:10,627 --> 00:20:13,255
"The report in its entirety,

364
00:20:13,297 --> 00:20:16,341
will cover youth activity..."

365
00:20:16,383 --> 00:20:19,344
"He's given me the divine
office to read every day,

366
00:20:19,386 --> 00:20:21,430
and the Penny Catechism."

367
00:20:21,471 --> 00:20:24,600
"Ah, the Penny Catechism.

368
00:20:24,641 --> 00:20:28,228
You might also consider reading
'The Confessions of St. Augustine,'

369
00:20:28,270 --> 00:20:31,481
which are
particularly good."

370
00:20:31,523 --> 00:20:34,776
"Anyway, Father Kahle
thinks I have made progress

371
00:20:34,818 --> 00:20:38,822
and we are not far away from the day
when I can make a full confession."

372
00:20:38,864 --> 00:20:41,325
"How wonderful.

373
00:20:41,366 --> 00:20:43,035
Be sure to tell me
what day it is

374
00:20:43,076 --> 00:20:45,287
that I might pray
for you myself."

375
00:20:45,329 --> 00:20:47,331
What's that,
Lord Longford?

376
00:20:47,372 --> 00:20:51,460
Uh, this is
the much-anticipated

377
00:20:51,502 --> 00:20:53,212
Youth Report
which I'm delivering

378
00:20:53,253 --> 00:20:56,465
- to the Prime Minister today.
- How long have you been working on it?

379
00:20:56,507 --> 00:20:58,842
I've been working
on it for 18 months.

380
00:21:02,262 --> 00:21:04,097
Any further questions?

381
00:21:06,058 --> 00:21:08,393
Very good.

382
00:21:08,435 --> 00:21:10,062
Bye.

383
00:21:11,563 --> 00:21:15,734
Oh, Frank, yesterday I finished
reading St. Augustine.

384
00:21:17,528 --> 00:21:21,281
The way he rejected his former life
and sinfulness...

385
00:21:23,659 --> 00:21:25,827
Afterwards, I lay
in my cell unable to sleep,

386
00:21:25,869 --> 00:21:28,038
my head was spinning so.

387
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:32,751
Every fiber in my body
seems to want to resist this,

388
00:21:32,793 --> 00:21:36,547
yet a part of me cannot deny
it feels so good too.

389
00:21:39,883 --> 00:21:42,177
I just keep hearing
Ian's voice in my head

390
00:21:42,219 --> 00:21:45,305
mocking me for my hypocrisy
and my insincerity.

391
00:21:46,723 --> 00:21:49,184
I wouldn't worry about that.

392
00:22:00,737 --> 00:22:03,156
Lord Longford, the Prime
Minister will see you now.

393
00:22:03,198 --> 00:22:05,200
Oh, thank you very much.

394
00:22:14,168 --> 00:22:16,211
- Prime Minister.
- Sit down, Frank.

395
00:22:20,132 --> 00:22:22,593
I'm gonna come
straight to the point.

396
00:22:22,593 --> 00:22:26,013
I want to give Shackleton a run
as leader of the House of Lords.

397
00:22:28,974 --> 00:22:30,851
I see.

398
00:22:30,893 --> 00:22:33,478
I want to thank you for everything
you've done for us, Frank.

399
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:35,731
You've done a terrific job
over the years.

400
00:22:35,772 --> 00:22:39,443
But you've
reached an age now.

401
00:22:39,484 --> 00:22:41,320
Shackleton's
a younger man.

402
00:22:43,071 --> 00:22:46,158
It... it's nothing to do
with the report, is it?

403
00:22:47,367 --> 00:22:48,994
What report?

404
00:22:51,121 --> 00:22:52,873
The Youth Report,
Prime Minister,

405
00:22:52,915 --> 00:22:55,250
that you
asked me to write.

406
00:22:55,292 --> 00:22:56,793
No no no.

407
00:22:56,835 --> 00:22:59,296
Nothing to do with that.

408
00:22:59,296 --> 00:23:02,049
I just want to give
Shackleton a run.

409
00:23:02,090 --> 00:23:04,343
As you know, we're right up
against it now.

410
00:23:04,384 --> 00:23:06,345
Tories have
gained ground and...

411
00:23:06,386 --> 00:23:08,305
you've gotta keep
moving in politics.

412
00:23:08,347 --> 00:23:10,224
Fresh blood,
new faces.

413
00:23:10,265 --> 00:23:12,184
New ideas.

414
00:23:41,171 --> 00:23:43,632
Everyone's down
having breakfast.

415
00:23:49,096 --> 00:23:51,014
Will you join us?

416
00:23:56,562 --> 00:23:59,398
Nice pieces in the paper.

417
00:23:59,439 --> 00:24:01,441
Yes.

418
00:24:01,483 --> 00:24:03,068
People are being
very kind.

419
00:24:03,110 --> 00:24:06,446
"The last remaining example
of a politician with principle."

420
00:24:11,118 --> 00:24:13,161
I'll leave the post.

421
00:24:15,372 --> 00:24:18,333
Not another one from Myra Hindley
by any chance?

422
00:24:18,375 --> 00:24:21,670
Because I've noticed she's been
writing to you a lot recently.

423
00:24:22,713 --> 00:24:24,798
Yes.

424
00:24:24,840 --> 00:24:28,343
I've been working towards her return
to the Catholic church.

425
00:24:29,887 --> 00:24:32,347
- Myra Hindley?
- Yes.

426
00:24:34,016 --> 00:24:36,643
Anyway, it's not from Myra,
it's from somebody else.

427
00:25:42,709 --> 00:25:44,211
Lord Longford.

428
00:25:44,294 --> 00:25:46,255
Mr. Brady.

429
00:25:48,841 --> 00:25:51,802
How good of you
not to disappoint.

430
00:25:53,220 --> 00:25:55,806
It's wonderful, isn't it,
when people look

431
00:25:55,848 --> 00:25:57,850
exactly as you imagine?

432
00:25:59,017 --> 00:26:01,103
So this is my competition...

433
00:26:01,144 --> 00:26:03,272
this is who
I'm up against.

434
00:26:04,898 --> 00:26:07,526
Myra's new boyfriend.

435
00:26:09,069 --> 00:26:11,655
She certainly
picks 'em, doesn't she?

436
00:26:13,031 --> 00:26:15,409
I did a little bit of research
before our meeting.

437
00:26:16,577 --> 00:26:18,912
I'd say there's
greater evidence of...

438
00:26:18,954 --> 00:26:22,291
mental instability
in your past than mine.

439
00:26:23,458 --> 00:26:26,420
Son and grandson
to military heroes,

440
00:26:26,503 --> 00:26:28,672
you were invalided
out of the army

441
00:26:28,714 --> 00:26:30,966
because of
a mental breakdown.

442
00:26:31,008 --> 00:26:34,052
Was it the full
crack-up, I wonder...

443
00:26:34,094 --> 00:26:35,929
or were you
just a coward?

444
00:26:37,181 --> 00:26:39,641
What can I do
for you, Mr. Brady?

445
00:26:39,683 --> 00:26:42,060
I'd like to find
my way back to God...

446
00:26:43,270 --> 00:26:45,981
Lord Longford.

447
00:26:46,023 --> 00:26:48,025
Will you help me?

448
00:26:48,066 --> 00:26:51,069
Why, certainly,
if that's what you...

449
00:26:51,111 --> 00:26:54,031
Don't you fuckin' dare.
You start with that pious mumbo-jumbo,

450
00:26:54,031 --> 00:26:56,533
I will jump across that table
and bite out your tongue.

451
00:26:56,575 --> 00:26:59,828
No. This present visit is
for your benefit, not mine.

452
00:27:01,455 --> 00:27:03,415
I want to tell you
about Myra,

453
00:27:03,457 --> 00:27:07,419
who you no doubt believe is sincere
in her religious conversion.

454
00:27:09,296 --> 00:27:12,090
Let me tell you,
that woman...

455
00:27:12,132 --> 00:27:13,884
cares no more about God

456
00:27:13,926 --> 00:27:17,221
than she cares about
the piles in my ass.

457
00:27:18,388 --> 00:27:20,849
What she cares about...

458
00:27:20,891 --> 00:27:22,643
is getting out.

459
00:27:23,685 --> 00:27:26,021
And she thinks
you'll help her.

460
00:27:26,063 --> 00:27:28,357
But the minute
your back is turned...

461
00:27:29,566 --> 00:27:31,360
she mocks you...

462
00:27:32,402 --> 00:27:33,946
for your silly hair

463
00:27:33,987 --> 00:27:37,199
and... and your clothes

464
00:27:37,241 --> 00:27:39,868
and your "self-important
autobiographies

465
00:27:39,910 --> 00:27:43,288
only published because his family
owns a bloody publishing house."

466
00:27:47,668 --> 00:27:49,878
What?

467
00:27:49,920 --> 00:27:52,548
She didn't tell you
she was still writing to me?

468
00:27:53,924 --> 00:27:55,801
No.

469
00:27:55,843 --> 00:27:57,553
Oh dear.

470
00:27:59,263 --> 00:28:01,181
She probably
didn't tell you

471
00:28:01,223 --> 00:28:03,684
she was fucking that little
prison officer either...

472
00:28:03,767 --> 00:28:05,227
a nun.

473
00:28:11,191 --> 00:28:14,319
They do it under the bed
in her cell, apparently.

474
00:28:16,196 --> 00:28:18,073
Four times a day.

475
00:28:19,241 --> 00:28:21,451
She has a very high
sex drive, our Myra.

476
00:28:23,245 --> 00:28:26,373
It's the sort of detail you might
want about your new girlfriend.

477
00:28:26,415 --> 00:28:28,125
She needs it
all the time.

478
00:28:28,166 --> 00:28:30,252
Like a man
in that way.

479
00:28:31,837 --> 00:28:33,922
Like a man
in other ways too.

480
00:28:35,007 --> 00:28:37,259
She's strong.

481
00:28:38,969 --> 00:28:41,430
That came in handy,
as you can imagine...

482
00:28:42,973 --> 00:28:46,018
when they were wriggling
and trying to get away.

483
00:28:46,059 --> 00:28:49,062
Wait, you can't go yet.
I haven't finished with you.

484
00:28:50,189 --> 00:28:52,816
Take my advice,

485
00:28:52,858 --> 00:28:55,110
go back to your
other prisoners...

486
00:28:55,152 --> 00:28:59,198
nice, uncomplicated ones
with broken noses

487
00:28:59,239 --> 00:29:01,450
and knuckle tattoos.

488
00:29:03,535 --> 00:29:06,163
Stay clear of Myra
because she will destroy you.

489
00:29:11,043 --> 00:29:13,170
She certainly destroyed me.

490
00:29:14,838 --> 00:29:17,466
And there... there's a thought
you've not had before:

491
00:29:19,051 --> 00:29:21,220
that Myra
egged me on...

492
00:29:23,013 --> 00:29:26,099
that without her, none of it
would have happened.

493
00:29:26,141 --> 00:29:28,477
Wait. You're not yet
dismissed!

494
00:29:28,519 --> 00:29:31,230
Listen to the tape,
that's my advice,

495
00:29:31,271 --> 00:29:33,732
if you want to know
what she's really like.

496
00:29:34,816 --> 00:29:37,069
And when you do listen,

497
00:29:37,110 --> 00:29:38,862
bear this in mind...

498
00:29:38,904 --> 00:29:41,615
it was her that insisted

499
00:29:41,657 --> 00:29:44,576
they call us...
"Mommy!"

500
00:29:44,618 --> 00:29:48,038
And "Daddy!"
Not me!

501
00:30:02,052 --> 00:30:03,762
Are you
all right, sir?

